BACKGROUND: Lumbosacral and coccygeal skin covered appendages are a rare 
malformation, considered human-tails.
CASE REPORT: The authors describe the case of a full term newborn girl with 
lumbar skin appendage and a normal neurologic examination. The magnetic 
resonance of the spine revealed a dermal sinus continuous with the skin 
appendage and with extension into to the spinal canal. Due to the infection 
risk, a surgery was performed on the third day of life, with dermal sinus 
ligation and appendage removal. At 12 months of follow-up the girl has a normal 
neurologic examination.
CONCLUSIONS: With the description of this case the authors aim to emphasize that 
although rare, lumbar skin appendages can be associated with spinal dysraphism 
and other lesions, requiring extensive work-up and long-term surveillance.

